This V-E Day, we’re remembering the #HomeportHeroes who served in Canada’s Merchant Navy and aided Allied victory in the Second World War. 

From December 1941 until the end of the war in 1945, Canadian shipyards on both coasts, and along the St. Lawrence River, undertook a massive emergency shipbuilding campaign to deliver hundreds of desperately-needed vessels to support the Allied war effort. Naval ships like destroyer HMCS Haida National Historic Site escorted merchant convoys to protect against submarine and air attacks. #LestWeForget http://ow.ly/79eS30brkUz

Not long after gold was discovered in large quantities in the Klondike, dredges were brought into the Yukon. One of the two dozen dredges that worked this area, Dredge No. 4 is 2/3 the size of a football field and more than seven stories high! It could dig in an hour what took three men all day. Find out more about the Klondike National Historic Sites: http://ow.ly/QQab30b3p3K Parks Canada Yukon Travel Yukon 

To celebrate #Canada150, we're featuring ALL of our 200+ places across our social media accounts. Did you know 2017 also marks the centennial of national historic sites? Stay tuned!

First built during the War of 1812 to defend the St. Lawrence River shipping route from attack by the United States, Fort Wellington National Historic Site helped thwart another American invasion during the 1837-38 Upper and Lower Canada rebellions. caption_original: A Swainson’s hawk was sitting on a fencepost, eating its prey (a northern pocket gopher) when I stopped well back to have a look. Although I used a telephoto lens and was trying not to bother it, after stripping off and gulping a few bits of meat from this headless snack, the hawk decided it wanted to nosh the rest without an audience, and took off (dramatically) to find a solitary perch.Swainson’s Hawks show up for our prescribed fires. Once the smoke starts rising, Swainson’s will be attracted to forage for mice/voles/shrews who have no more grass cover to hide in. We’ve seen as many as or hawks in one area that has been recently burned.Over species (301 at the last official count) use the Last Mountain Lake National Wildlife Area for breeding (180 species) and passing through on migration.People like Kerry monitor nesting success of these large hawks at the LML NWA. Come and see for yourself at our open house June -6pm....

A new restriction temporarily prohibits the import of all species of salamanders, newts and mudpuppies, for one-year, unless authorized by a permit issued by Environment and Climate Change Canada. 

A deadly disease-causing fungus, suspected to have spread from Asia via the pet trade, has been devastating salamander populations in Europe.  Wild salamanders play a vital role in Canada’s ecosystems as part of the food web and in nutrient and carbon cycling. If the fungus enters Canadian ecosystems, the impacts on our native salamanders could be devastating. http://ow.ly/zZLd30ccnnz

caption_original: It may not look like much but over the last year, scientists have been using these new solar-powered satellite transmitters to tag and track Thayer’s Gulls from the high arctic to BC. This data is helping scientists learn about the foraging and migrating behavior of this species, and how they overlap with areas of high marine shipping. Recently, a bird with a transmitter stopped moving. The signal remained strong, and coordinates indicated it was located in a remote area of Alaska. Scientists presumed the device lost until a local resident offered to help with the search. Equipped with his boat, GPS, and coordinates provided by ECCC, he found the transmitter on a remote beach off of Iyoukeen Bay – km from ! Thanks Mr. Chew!.....

caption_original:
Some 30 Canadian companies, from Loblaws, to Canadian Tire, to the five big banks, have come out strongly in support of a price on pollution.

Canadian companies are choosing cleaner options as they produce and sell their products. They are making their operations more efficient. And they are putting bold ideas into action and creating good-paying middle-class jobs and opportunities in the process.

Countries from China to Chile to those in the European Union, and American states like Oregon and California – the sixth largest economy in the world – are all pricing carbon pollution. 

These major economies are putting a price on carbon pollution because it works, and because it is the most effective way to reach our emissions reductions goals while growing strong economies.
caption_cleaned: Some Canadian companies, from Loblaws, to Canadian Tire, to the five big banks, have come out strongly in support of a price on pollution. Countries from China to Chile to those in the European Union, and American states like Oregon and California – the sixth largest economy in the world – are all pricing carbon pollution. A prepayment is a lump-sum payment that you make, in addition to regular mortgage payments, before the end of your mortgage term. The prepayment reduces your outstanding balance and allows you to pay off your mortgage faster.

caption_original:
"We were returning from Baltimore to Toronto when our flight was cancelled due to poor weather. The airline rebooked us 5 days later because that was their only flight which had availability. Although there was availability on their partner flight, they would not book us on another airline. We could not wait for 5 days to return home, as a result, we purchased new flights. We tried to work with the airline to receive a refund but they refused to offer any compensation. Consequently, we turned to the Canadian Transportation Agency for assistance. Their service was amazing- very thorough, very comprehensive and very attentive. The first contact explained the passenger tariff and our rights as passengers. We took the next step and asked CTA to mediate on our behalf, which fortunately turned out to be a successful exercise. We were very impressed with the support we received and the professionalism of the staff at CTA. It is sad that the state of airline travel in Canada requires an agency such as the CTA but it is reassuring to know that they are there to help ensure passenger rights are met."

Marci

http://ow.ly/gv1230cASUR
caption_cleaned: "We were returning from Baltimore to Toronto when our flight was cancelled due to poor weather. The airline rebooked us days later because that was their only flight which had availability. Although there was availability on their partner flight, they would not book us on another airline. We could not wait for days to return home, as a result, we purchased new flights. We tried to work with the airline to receive a refund but they refused to offer any compensation. Consequently, we turned to the Canadian Transportation Agency for assistance. Their service was amazing- very thorough, very comprehensive and very attentive. The first contact elained the passenger tariff and our rights as passengers. We took the next step and asked CTA to mediate on our behalf, which fortunately turned out to be a successful exercise. We were very impressed with the support we received and the professionalism of the staff at CTA. It is sad that the state of airline travel in Canada requires an agency such as the CTA but it is reassuring to know that they are there to help ensure passenger rights are met." Marci

caption_original:
25 years ago, the UV Index was launched by Environment and Climate Change Canada’s scientists. Two years later, it was adopted by the World Health Organization and the United Nations Environment Program, and it is now used internationally. 

The UV Index is a measure of the strength of the sun’s UV rays. It is based on the thickness of the ozone layer in the upper atmosphere, the angle of the sun above the horizon and the amount of cloud cover.  As the UV increases, the sun’s rays can do more harm to your skin, eyes and immune system.

Congratulations to Environment and Climate Change Canada’s scientists for developing such a useful tool! 👍🏼 http://ow.ly/6aIy30c4DeP
caption_cleaned: years ago, the UV Index was launched by Environment and Climate Change Canada’s scientists. Two years later, it was adopted by the World Health Organization and the United Nations Environment Program, and it is now used internationally. caption_original:
Lake Erie needs your help! Harmful and nuisance algal blooms are hurting Lake Erie’s environment and economy, and present risks to human health. But a healthier lake is possible.

Canadians have until May 24 to comment on a draft action plan to help reduce the amount of phosphorus – a key factor causing algae – from entering the lake. Your comments and ideas will help build a final Plan with specific actions to help restore water quality in Lake Erie.

Public meetings are taking place on May 16 and 18 in the Lake Erie basin. Can’t make it in person?  Share your ideas online! www.letstalklakeerie.ca

Are you a recent college or university graduate? CONGRATS!

For the first six months after you leave school, you don’t have to make payments on your Canada Student Loan or your provincial student loan. But remember that interest DOES accumulate during this period.

Now’s the time to make a plan for repaying your student debt. You will need to know the total amount you owe, the interest rate that will be applied to your debt and how long it will take to pay back your debt.

Learn more about paying back Canada Student Loans: http://ow.ly/j3kN30bDPUH
